t1158.text: Elections are always held on Saturdays, and postal voting is well supported by our electoral system. Also we hold Federal Elections T least every 3 years, so higher opportunity for turnaround.

t1159.text: To this end, I always preferenced The Greens first (tho in my affluent seat, they’re essentially a non-entity, but thanks to preferential voting, I can at least be safe in knowing my vote is passed onto Labor, who have a more credible chance)

t1160.text: We use preferential voting in Australia, eliminating the need for “tactical voting”, where third-party candidates would be ignored for the sake of pragmatism, and minimising the pronounced two-party duopoly of the US and UK.

t1161.text: Electoral divisions are drawn up by an independent non-partisan commission, and gerrymandering is virtually non-existent in Australia.

t1162.text: In Australia, voting in elections is compulsory. Failure to vote is punishable by fines. This essentially eliminates suppression of voters of colour, which is rampant in British and particularly American elections.
